        Official Singles Chart Top 100 on 14/7/2023

        14 July 2023 - 20 July 2023

        The Official UK Singles Chart reflects the UK’s biggest songs of the week, based on audio and video streams, downloads, CDs and vinyl, compiled by the Official Charts Company. The UK Top 40 is broadcast on BBC Radio 1 and MTV, the Top 100 is published exclusively on OfficialCharts.com. View the biggest songs of 2024 so far.

        Chart Review 14/07/2023

        And with the sound of a gong that never stops ringing, I'm here. Even though I probably shouldn't be. Never stopped me though. This is the part of the paragraph where I warn you about the lack of chart movement. Only kidding! This week is full of 'stories'. And many of them are about Taylor Swift. Because when aren't they.

        Starting with the eye-gouingly obvious, however, and it seems that Dave is everywhere at the moment. Hiring him to appear in the announcemet trailer for that new EA Sports football game seemed a bit superfluous though. Surely this isn't 'too much exposure'? Eh, I don't care. Shame that Sprinter hasn't improved for though. Six weeks of chart and yet I can barely name any of the rhyming couplets. Am I just old?

        O-Rod is still at 2, and from consistently hearing this on the radio, I can officially comment on the fact that this song, ROCKS. It's great. Don't convince me otherwise. Also on the 'how is this THAT good for me' scale is Taylor Swift's Cruel Summer, which is now the third most brill song in the land. All because, erm, she went on tour. Who would've figured. On a more inconsistent note, Jack Saunders deciding to get random members of the public to yell out the verses instead of Swifty seemed, at best, odd. I'm one for left-field choices but this is ridiculous.

        Oh, and Speak Now (TV) was released last Friday. Didn't notice? Then you clearly aren't a human being. The No.
